ience, demonstrate how people made use of their new knowledge.Lynn’s study provides a clearer understanding of the role played by science in the Republic of Letters and the participation of the general population in the formation of public opinion on scientific matters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aScience and civilizationxHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezFrancexPublic opinionxHistoryy18th century. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aadvertisements.  aaudience.  acourse descriptions.  aeconomics.  aeighteenth-century France.  ageography.  apopular science.  apopularizers.  apublic lectures.  apublic opinion.  atheatrics.  aurban scientific culture.1 aLynn, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130457423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130457/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013